    q: "What's your framework for deciding agent autonomy levels in any system you design?",
    a: "**The framework — score every action type on four axes:**\n- **Reversibility:** can it be undone cheaply? Drafting an email is fully reversible; sending a wire transfer is not.\n- **Blast radius:** worst-case cost of a wrong action — one user annoyed, or production down, or legal exposure?\n- **Verifiability:** can correctness be checked automatically before or after? A generated SQL query can be validated and sandboxed; a judgment call to a customer cannot.\n- **Frequency:** high-volume actions both justify automation investment and generate the statistics needed to trust it.\n\n**Map scores to an autonomy ladder:**\n- **L0** — suggest only; human does everything\n- **L1** — agent prepares, human executes (one-click with review)\n- **L2** — agent executes within pre-approved rules, human approves exceptions\n- **L3** — agent executes autonomously, humans review post-hoc samples\n- **L4** — fully autonomous, monitoring only\n\n**The two rules that make it a framework instead of a vibe:**\n- **Autonomy is earned per action type, not granted per agent.** The same agent can be L3 on re-running diagnostics and permanently L1 on issuing refunds. 'How autonomous is your agent' is a malformed question; the unit of autonomy is the action.\n- **Promotion requires measured evidence at the current level** — acceptance rates, error rates over N executions, zero-harm history — with demotion triggers defined in advance (error rate above X → automatic drop to L1 + alert).\n\n**Enforcement is what makes the ladder real:** runtime budgets, tool allowlists per level, approval gates in the execution path (not the prompt), kill switches, and immutable audit logs. A ladder documented in Confluence but not enforced in the runtime is a diagram, not a control.\n\n**Worked example (support agent):** look up order — reversible, tiny blast radius, verifiable → L3 immediately. Issue refund — irreversible, money, partially verifiable → starts L1, earns L2 within coded caps after 1,000 clean approvals; above $X stays L1 by policy forever. Escalate to human — always available at every level, never gated.\n\n**Why interviewers love this:** it answers half of all agentic design questions — 'should the agent do X autonomously' stops being philosophy and becomes a scoring exercise with an evidence bar. State the framework early in any agent design and apply it consistently.\n\n**Likely follow-ups:**\n- Give an action you'd cap at L2 permanently regardless of track record, and defend it.\n- How does the evidence bar change between 100 executions and 100,000?\n- A model upgrade resets your confidence. Do all actions drop a level?\n- How would you present this ladder to a compliance team as a governance artifact?",
